Section 1 - Initial conversation

Rule for initiating conversation with Old Man Holstenoffer:
	change the chosen opening gambit to HO12;

[HO1 is a quip: see Germaise's Conversation, above.] The display text of HO1 is "Holstenoffer glances over his shoulder as you come in. 'Ey, Jack!' he calls. 'Long time, no see. Bobby was around this morning, looking for yeh. Up to something again, eh?' he laughs."

HO2 is a quip. The menu text is "'What did Bobby want?'". The display text is "[first time]'Bobby was looking for me?' you ask, trying to contain your excitement. 'Did he say what he wanted?'[paragraph break]Holstenoffer shrugs. 'Didn't say. He said he'd be waiting for you over by Lord's Market. Yeh oughtta stick by Bobby more, Jack,' he adds. 'Big strong lad, he is; do a skinny boy like yerself good to learn from him.'[subsequently][rp] 'you'll have to ask him yerself. He's somewhere around Lord's Market, east of here.'[only]"

HO3 is a quip. The menu text is "'Heard any gossip?'". The display text is "[first time]'So, heard any good gossip lately, Holstenoffer?' you ask.[paragraph break]'Well, the mercenaries in Grubber's have got everyone excited,' Holstenoffer says, 'but I expect they'll be old news by tomorrow. Aside from that, all anyone talks about is the upcoming Ascension, yeh know.'[subsequently][rp] 'mercenaries and the Ascension are all anyone's talking about.'[only]"

HO4 is a quip. The menu text is "'What do you know about the mercenaries in Grubber's?'". The display text is "[first time]'Have you heard about the mercenaries in Grubber's Market this morning?' you ask.[paragraph break]Holstenoffer's eyes narrow. 'All I know about mercs is, they're filthy scavengers to a man, with empty purses where their sense of honor oughtta be. Let [']em try coming up Commerce Street,' he growls, tightening his grip on his cleaver, 'They'll find more than some timid stallkeeper here!'[subsequently][rp] 'all I know is they'd better not come into my shop.'[only]"

HO5 is a quip. The menu text is "'What do you think about Baron Fossville?'". The display text is "[first time]'So tell us what you [i]really[r] think of Baron Fossville,' you say, smiling at Hostenoffer's earlier impression.[paragraph break]The butcher's face suddenly grows dark, and his cleaver [i]thwacks[r] into the wooden block. 'Tell yeh the truth Jack, I laugh about it when I can, but the Baron's a rat and I'm not afraid to say it. He don't care about this city, he don't care for anything but his own purse and his own power, and he ain't half the lord the old Duke was. He and the old Duke were always at odds, yeh know. But Fossville won that quarrel, and not by playing fair, I'd wager.' Holstenoffer shakes his cleaver menacingly. 'It makes a man so angry, he's liable to cut his own hand off if he's not careful.'[subsequently][rp] 'Fossville's a rat and everyone knows it.'[only]"

HO6 is a quip. The menu text is "'What do you think of the Queen?'". The display text is "[first time]'What do you think of the Queen?' you ask.[paragraph break]'Bah,' spits Holstenoffer, 'that old bat couldn't rule so much as her own temper. This whole kingdom went to pot when she took the throne, and we'll be even worse off if she gets to decide who takes the throne after her.'[subsequently][rp] 'her Royal Highness is an idiot. She'll run this kingdom into the ground before she's through.'[only]"

HO7 is a quip. The menu text is "'What do you think of the Princess?'". The display text is "[first time]'What do you think of the Princess?' you ask.[paragraph break]'Well, the apple doesn't fall too far from the tree, yeh know,' grumbles Holstenoffer. 'I figure if the Ascension goes to the Queen's little brat, it'll be just like she never left.'[subsequently][rp] 'I just hope the nobles can decide on someone better to rule this kingdom.'[only]"

HO8 is a quip. The menu text is "'What do you think of the Ascension?'". The display text is "[first time]'What's your opinion of the upcoming Ascension?' you ask. 'Who do you think will take the throne?'[paragraph break]Holstenoffer heaves a sigh and spreads his arms in a wide shrug (forcing you to duck as a bit of bloody suet flies off the end of his cleaver and [i]splats[r] against the wall). 'I'm just a humble butcher, Jack. I know chopping meat, not Royal politics. But I do know that Fossville has his eye on the Queen's daughter, and that means his eye is on the throne, and [i]that[r] means no good for anyone. Yeh know what I think?' he asks, squinting at you and pointing with his cleaver. 'Old Holstenoffer thinks we're all doomed. That's what I think.'[subsequently][rp] 'it's all about who marries the Queen's daughter. Too depressing to think about, really.'[only]"

HO9 is a quip. The menu text is "'What did you think of the old Duke?'". The display text is "[first time]'I guess you liked the old Duke better, huh?' you ask.[paragraph break]Holstenoffer takes a deep breath. 'It's hard for someone your age to understand, Jack,' he says. 'Duke Toresal was a great man. A great, great man.' He starts chopping furiously, as if trying to hide a sudden rush of emotion.[subsequently][rp] 'the old Duke was a great man.'[only]"

HO10 is a quip. The menu text is "'Where did you get the tattoos?'". The display text is "[first time]'Holstenoffer,' you ask, 'where did you get those tattoos?'[paragraph break]Holstenoffer looks proudly down at his arms. 'Got these during my days at sea,' he said. 'I was quite the old salty dog, yeh know, before I came back to the city to be a meat chopper.' Then he frowns. 'Never did get the hang of it, though,' he admits. 'Kept gettin['] seasick. Still, the tattoos are quite the conversation piece, they are.'[subsequently][rp] 'got [']em when I was a sailor.'[only]"

HO11 is a quip. The menu text is "'Thanks.'". The display text is "'Thanks, Holstenoffer,' you say.[paragraph break]'Always a pleasure,' he says, bringing his cleaver down with a crunch."

HO12 is a quip. The menu text is "'Can I ask you something?'". The display text is "'Mind if I ask you a question?' you say.[paragraph break]'Go right ahead,' says Holstenoffer."

HO13 is a quip. The menu text is "'Never mind.'". The display text is "'Nah, never mind, it was nothing.'[paragraph break]'Suit yourself,' Holstenoffer says with a shrug."

HO14 is a quip. The display text is "'Say, Jack,' says Holstenoffer suddenly, 'I haven't seen Widow Shannon down this way in a few days. Everything all right at Maiden House?'"

HO15 is a quip. The menu text is "'She's fine; she's just been busy.'". The display text is "'Oh, everything's fine at Maiden House,' you say, while thinking to yourself, [i]and boring as ever[r]. 'Widow Shannon's just been busy; she hasn't had time to do the shopping.'[paragraph break]'Well, tell her I've been savin['] some choice cuts for her next time she comes down here. Good meat, better than she'll get in Grubber's, and cheaper too. Those orphans need to eat healthy.' He grins. 'And I need to convince Widow Shannon that I'd make her a good husband.'"

HO16 is a quip. The menu text is "'I try to stay away from Maiden House.'". The display text is "You try to stifle a groan. 'To tell you the truth, Holstenoffer, I try to stay away from Maiden House whenever I can.'[paragraph break]Holstenoffer smiles knowingly. 'The widows breathin['] down yer neck a bit, eh? Well, I know all about that. Plenty a['] times I sneaked outta the bedroom window when I was a wee lad stayin['] with me aunty. Still,' he waves his cleaver at you admonishingly, and you step back quickly to avoid a deep facial scar. 'Still, Maiden House is a good place for urchins like yerself. Keeps yeh outta trouble. And the widows are a fine bunch of women. [i]Especially[r] that Shannon,' he adds, with a wistful look in his eye."

HO17 is a quip. The menu text is "'She's just not into you, Holstenoffer.'". The display text is "You sigh. 'You know, I've told you before, Widow Shannon isn't looking for a husband. It's nothing against you personally, I think she just likes devoting all her time to the orphans.'[paragraph break]Holstenoffer just smiles. 'Oh, I know, Jack, that's what she [i]says[r]. But old Holstenoffer knows a few tricks too, yeh know.' He waves his cleaver in the air nonchalantly; a bit of bloody gristle dangles from the blade's tip. 'You just get her down here, and let Holstenoffer work his charm.'[paragraph break]You know from past experience that there's no use arguing with him about this, so you just smile and nod. 'I'll let her know,' you say."

