Chapter 2 - Further Conversation

DS31 is a quip. The display text is "Dame Sandler looks you over and smiles. She does not seem at all surprised by your change in dress.[paragraph break]'Lady Jacqueline,' she says, inclining her head, 'how nice to see you finally looking yourself, after all these years. Come, child, let me get a look at you.' She takes your chin gently between finger and thumb and tilts your face back and forth. 'Hmm. You've simply destroyed your hair, of course, but there's nothing to be done now. It will grow out eventually.'"

DS32 is a quip. The menu text is "'You knew I was a girl all along?'". The display text is "Dame Sandler laughs, not unkindly. 'Oh, child, did you really think I hadn't guessed? It's not that great a secret, you know; more people have had their eye on you than you realize. We've all been waiting for the Duke's daughter to finally make herself known, and now here you are.'"

DS33 is a transitional quip. The menu text is "'Who's had their eye on me?'". The display text is "'What do you mean, [']had their eye on me[']?' you say, all your old suspicions returning. 'Who else knew? Who's been watching me?'"
The following quip is DS38.

DS34 is a quip. The menu text is "'Widow Fiona sent me.'". The display text is "'Widow Fiona sent me,' you say. 'She said that you could help me.'[paragraph break]Dame Sandler nods. 'I know, child. I've been expecting her to send you to me any day now. I'm sorry I couldn't help you before, but we — Fiona and I — dared not risk Baron Fossville discovering that I knew who you were. I was only to step in as a last resort, when the Baron had tracked you down and chased you from every other hiding place.'"

DS35 is a quip. The menu text is "'You and Fiona planned all this?'". The display text is "'So you and Widow Fiona planned all this? You knew she was really working for the — for my father?' you ask. Your head is spinning with conspiracies; no one is who they seem to be.[paragraph break]'Fiona and I have known each other for a long time,' Dame Sandler says, 'since before you were born. She sought my help when your father died. We had our suspicions even then, and we made plans in case the worst should come to pass.'"

DS36 is a transitional quip. The menu text is "'Suspicions?'". The display text is "'Suspicions?' you ask. 'Suspicions of what?'[paragraph break]Dame Sandler looks down at her hands for a long time. When she looks up at you again, you are shocked to see tears in her eyes. 'Fossville may have murdered your father.'"
The following quip is DS41.

DS37 is a transitional quip. The menu text is "'Why is Fossville after me?'". The display text is "'But why does Fossville hate me so much?' you cry. 'I just don't understand any of this — I've never done anything to him!'"
The following quip is DS38.

DS38 is a quip. The display text is "Dame Sandler sighs and her expression turns serious. 'What you must realize, Jacqueline, is that you represent a threat to certain people with ambitions toward the throne. The laws of ascension in our land are quite clear: in the absence of a named successor, the ruler is determined by the will of the people.'[paragraph break]She gives you a long, significant look. 'The Duke — your father — was very popular with the common people. Baron Fossville... is not.'[paragraph break]Your mouth goes dry, and the floor seems to tilt beneath your feet for a moment. 'Are you saying...'[paragraph break]'Yes,' says Dame Sandler. 'I am saying that you have a credible claim to the throne.'"

DS39 is a quip. The menu text is "'That's ridiculous.'". The display text is "You try to catch your breath, but it's all you can do to keep from bursting out into hysterical giggles. 'But that's just... ridiculous,' you say. 'Completely ridiculous. I can't take the [i]throne[r], I'm just an orphan, a street girl, a [i]nobody[r]...'[paragraph break]'You are the daughter of one of the most loved and respected noblemen in living memory,' Dame Sandler says quietly. 'If the Duke were alive today there is no question that he would take the Ascension if he so desired it. As his heir — even as his illegitimate heir — much of that esteem would fall to you. Many would think you worthy.'"

DS40 is a transitional quip. The menu text is "'Is that the only reason Fossville hates me?'". The display text is "'So that's it? That's why Fossville hates me and wants to lock me away?' you ask. 'Because he thinks I'll get the throne instead of him?'[paragraph break]Dame Sandler looks down at her hands for a long time. 'There may be one other reason,' she says. 'Many suspect this, but few will speak of it.' When she looks up at you again, you are shocked to see tears in her eyes. 'Fossville may have murdered your father.'"
The following quip is DS41.

DS41 is a quip. The display text is "Your stomach feels as though you are falling down a deep hole, but on the outside, you are still and calm. You think you should be surprised, but somehow, you know you had been expecting this all along.[paragraph break]'How did he do it?' you whisper.[paragraph break]'Poison seems most obvious,' Dame Sandler says, regaining a measure of control. 'But no one really knows. There's never been any proof.'[paragraph break]You nod. You feel anger, but it's a smoldering, far away anger. It is something you will have to deal with later. Right now, there are too many other things you need to know."

DS42 is a quip. The menu text is "'How would I take the throne?'". The display text is "'Even if I do have a... a credible claim to the throne,' you ask, 'what would I do with it? How am I supposed to take the Ascension? I can't just walk around Grubber's Market shouting, [i]I'm the Duke's daughter, vote for me![r]' You think about it for a moment, then add, 'Can I?'[paragraph break]Dame Sandler smiles. 'Well, the other thing you must realize is that there are also a number of people who are interested in seeing you succeed, and who can help you press your claim. Some of them may believe that you are the better candidate; more of them simply want to spite Fossville; all of them will expect you to be appropriately grateful for their aid should you actually succeed. It is a very valuable commodity, the gratitude of a queen.'"

DS43 is a quip. The menu text is "'I can't do this.'". The display text is "You shake your head. 'I can't do this. I can't rule a kingdom, it's... it's just insane.'[paragraph break]Dame Sandler puts a hand on your arm. 'I realize this is a bit sudden and frightening, my dear, but you must accept it and act quickly.' Her voice is soothing, but firm. 'This will not simply go away. Fossville does not care whether you want the Ascension. He will hunt you down regardless. So why not take him head-on? This is who you are, now. Enjoy it, play it to the hilt.'"

DS44 is a quip. The menu text is "'What do I have to do?'". The display text is "You take a long, deep breath. Part of you still can't believe this is even happening. But you hear yourself saying, 'All right. What do I have to do?'[paragraph break]'Before you can enlist anyone's aid,' says Dame Sandler, 'you must let it be known that you are in the game, and that you are a player worth backing. You must announce yourself. And to do that, you must attend Fossville's ball tonight.'[paragraph break]In spite of everything that's happened, you find yourself smiling at the idea of attending a royal ball.[paragraph break]'Of course, you cannot attend the ball looking like this,' Dame Sandler says, her tone becoming brisk and businesslike again. 'You will need three things: a dress, some jewelry... and a weapon.'"

DS45 is a quip. The menu text is "'Where can I get a dress?'". The display text is "You look down at the dress you're wearing, the one Shannon found in Red Gate Estate.[paragraph break]'You mean this dress isn't good enough?' you ask, a bit hurt. 'Where can I get a better one?'[paragraph break]Dame Sandler smiles sympathetically. 'It's very nice, Jacqueline, but I'm afraid it's just a little bit out of fashion. The clothier right next door should be able to fit you with something more appropriate.'"

DS46 is a quip. The menu text is "'Why do I need a weapon?'". The display text is "'A weapon?' you ask. 'Why do I need a weapon at a fancy ball?'[paragraph break]'I admit it's unlikely that Fossville would try to kill you in front of a hundred guests,' Dame Sandler says drily, 'but you can never be too careful. There's a weapons dealer on Commerce Street who should have what you need.'"

DS47 is a quip. The menu text is "'How am I going to pay for this?'". The display text is "'I appreciate your advice, Dame Sandler,' you say, 'but how am I going to pay for all this? I don't have any money.'[paragraph break]'Ah, but you have something even better than money, Jacqueline,' Dame Sandler says. 'You have credibility. Go to the Chorus Brothers here in Lord's Market. Show them proof of your heritage, and they should be more than willing to help you with money.'"

DS48 is a quip. The menu text is "'Where can I get some jewelry?'". The display text is "'Where am I going to get some jewelry?' you ask. It occurs to you that you had a very nice necklace, but then you gave it to a monkey...[paragraph break]'Let me take care of that,' Dame Sandler says. She unlocks the display case with a tiny silver key, lifts up the lid, and gestures to the sparkling jewels within. 'Take any one you like, child. I'm one of those who would see you succeed; this is my gift to you.'"

DS49 is a quip. The menu text is "'Thank you.'". The display text is "'I hardly know what to say, Dame Sandler,' you breathe. 'Thank you.'[paragraph break]She merely smiles and inclines her head. 'Now hurry — Fossville's ball is tonight, and there's not much time left. See the moneylenders first, then get a suitable dress and a discreet blade. Pieter will go with you—'[paragraph break]Pieter blinks. 'What, to the ball?' he asks.[paragraph break]'Yes, Pieter,' Sandler says pointedly, 'to the ball. Just do what you always do — keep your mouth shut and make sure no one harms the valuables.'[paragraph break]She turns back to you and smiles 'Go, child, and good luck.'"

DS49B is a quip. The display text is "'A fine choice,' says Dame Sandler, closing and locking the case once again."

