The Baron of Amhyron is a male ballgoer. The description of the Baron of Amhyron is "Baron Amhyron is middle-aged, somewhat stout, with a red face and kind crinkles around his deep, brown eyes. His clothes are not quite as rich or as formal as those of some of the other guests, but he still cuts a respectable figure." Understand "lord", "falton", "man" as the Baron of Amhyron.

The distant description of the Baron of Amhyron is "The Baron of Amhyron is mingling near the banquet table. He looks a little overwhelmed, although he appears to be enjoying himself."

AM1 is a quip. The display text is "Amhyron smiles as you approach. 'Good evening, milady,' he says, bowing and taking your hand. 'I don't believe I've had the pleasure of an introduction. I am Lord Falton, Baron of Amhyron. And you are?'[paragraph break]'Lady Jacqueline,' you manage, 'of, er... of Toresal.'[paragraph break]The Baron's eyebrows lift slightly. 'Do tell. How... intriguing. How may I be of service to you this evening, Lady Jacqueline?'"

AM2 is a quip. The menu text is "'I'm surprised you don't know who I am.'". The display text is "'I'm surprised you don't know who I am already,' you say with a smile. 'It sometimes seems like everyone else here does.'[paragraph break]'I didn't recognize you at first, no,' says the Baron, 'But I can't say I've never heard of you. There were rumors that the old Duke Toresal had a child hidden away somewhere, but I never gave them much thought. As to why you're here, I think I can guess.' He smiles. 'I suppose you're something of a stick in Fossville's spokes. Aren't you worried he'll come after you?'"

AM3 is a quip. The menu text is "'He's already tried.'". The display text is "'He's already tried, more than once,' you say, proudly. 'He hasn't caught me yet.'[paragraph break]The Baron's smile broadens. 'You certainly seem like a capable young woman,' he says. 'I suppose it's him I should be worried about.'"

AM4 is a quip. The menu text is "'He doesn't know I'm here.'". The display text is "'I doubt it,' you say. 'I don't think he even knows I'm here. I kind of snuck in through the back door,' you confide.[paragraph break]The Baron frowns slightly. 'But he'll find out soon enough, especially with everyone at the ball talking about you. And they are definitely talking about you, by the way,' he adds, with a slight smile. 'You should probably be more careful.'"

AM5 is a quip. The menu text is "'You look like you'd rather be somewhere else.'". The display text is "'You look like you'd rather be somewhere else,' you say. 'In fact, if you don't mind my saying so, you're the only person I've met so far who looks as uncomfortable as I feel. I thought a nobleman like yourself would be right at home at a fancy party like this.'[paragraph break]The Baron spreads his hands and shrugs. 'I'm something of an outsider here, I'm afraid,' he says. 'Just like you. I'm not very good at idle conversation, and I'm not important enough for anyone to want to chat me up.'"

AM6 is a quip. The menu text is "'Would you support me in the Ascension?'". The display text is "Something about the Baron's manner puts you at ease, and you decide to take the direct approach. 'Listen,' you say, 'uh, milord. The only reason I'm here is because I need allies. I don't have very many, and the truth is, I'm not very good at getting more, and I'm getting kind of desperate. So I'm going to come right out and say it. You know who I am... would you be willing to support me in the Ascension?'[paragraph break]The Baron, who has listened to you carefully throughout your whole speech, looks down at the floor and sighs.[paragraph break]'Thank you for your candor, Lady Jacqueline,' he says finally, looking you in the eye. 'I will try to be equally honest. I'd support just about anyone against Fossville. And I would be overjoyed to support the heir of Duke Toresal most especially. Unfortunately, that may not mean very much. I couldn't garner much more support beyond my own single vote, first of all. I haven't the influence.'[paragraph break]The Baron pauses, then looks away. 'And secondly, I can't oppose Duke Inhyron's interests without putting myself in jeopardy,' he says quietly. 'He's the one you need to convince, not me.'"

AM7 is a quip. The menu text is "'Why can't you act against Inhyron?'". The display text is "'What makes you so beholden to Inhyron?' you ask. 'Can't you speak your own mind?'[paragraph break]'Oh, I speak my mind often,' the Baron says quickly. 'Everyone pretty much ignores me. Or else they smile condescendingly and say how nice it is that the common folk have someone to represent their interests. And so it goes.'[paragraph break]He heaves another sigh. 'As for why I am so beholden, my family's land and titles were gifted by Inhyron's ancestor. That means he can remove them whenever he likes.'"

AM8 is a quip. The menu text is "'Would that be so bad?'". The display text is "'Would it be so bad if he did?' you press. 'You can't be happy serving under him like that.'[paragraph break]'You're right, I'm not very happy,' concedes the Baron. 'I'd give it all away, lands and title, except... except if Inhyron removed me, he'd replace me with someone worse — probably himself. I've managed to do some good in my little corner of Miradania, and I don't want to leave my subjects to someone who's just going to treat them like... well, like peasants. Better to stay where I am and do what I can, then to make waves and lose the ability to do even that much.'"

AM9 is a quip. The menu text is "'If I become Queen, I could help you.'". The display text is "'If I became Queen, I could help you,' you point out. 'I could grant you Royal lands, or something. You could be independent of Inhyron.'[paragraph break]The Baron grins wrily. 'That would be wonderful,' he says. 'But you can't make me independent of the Duke until you're Queen. And to become Queen, you'll need support. And I can't support you until I'm independent of the Duke. And so it goes.' He chuckles. 'I'm afraid my hands are tied, Lady Jacqueline.'"

AM10 is a quip. The menu text is "'What do you know about Fossville?'". The display text is "'What do you know about Fossville?' you ask.[paragraph break]'Hmm. Fossville, well.' The Baron pauses, carefully choosing his words. 'I don't like him. He is motivated purely by personal ambition; I don't think he cares a whit about the welfare of his subjects or about actually running the Kingdom, and that will spell disaster for Miradania if he takes the throne. That would be bad enough, but then there are the allegations about how the old Duke Toresal died... I would oppose his candidacy if I could, of course, but even then I'm afraid I wouldn't have enough influence for that to mean very much.'"
The repeat text is "[rp] 'I don't like him, but I can't openly oppose him if Inhyron supports him.'"

AM11 is a quip. The menu text is "'Did you know my father?'". The display text is "'Did you know my father?' you ask.[paragraph break]'Not personally, milady,' the Baron says, 'but from what I understand he was beloved by his subjects and respected by his fellow noblemen. Many people were sorry when he died.'"
The repeat text is "[rp] 'he was a good man and I was sorry when he passed on.'"

AM12 is a quip. The menu text is "'What do you think of Jacobs?'". The display text is "'What do you think of Jacobs the Elder?' you ask.[paragraph break]'Jacobs is an... interesting character,' says the Baron. 'I'm not quite sure what to make of him, except that he's probably not one to trifle with. And certainly not one to make casual deals with, unless you enjoy losing the shirt off your back without ever realizing that you'd wagered it.'"
The repeat text is "[rp] 'he's a tricky fellow. I hope you didn't promise him anything.'"

AM13 is a quip. The menu text is "'What do you think of the Queen?'". The display text is "'What do you think of the Queen?' you ask.[paragraph break]'The Queen is being short-sighted,' the Baron says. 'She's backing Fossville because she wants to maintain her family's dynasty, but she's not considering what that would mean for the Kingdom as a whole. I have no doubt that she'd as easily switch to some other candidate, but whomever she backs, she'll back for the wrong reasons.'"
The repeat text is "[rp] 'the Queen will back whomever helps her most politically, without regard for the consequences.'"

AM14 is a quip. The menu text is "'What do you think of the Princess?'". The display text is "'What do you think of the Princess?' you ask. [paragraph break]The Baron smiles. 'Well, the Princess is young,' he says. 'You can't really blame her for wanting the same thing her mother wants, now can you?'"
The repeat text is "[rp] 'the Princess is young. I tend to give her the benefit of the doubt for that.'"

AM15 is a quip. The menu text is "'What do you think of the Duke of Inhyron?'". The display text is "'What do you think of the Duke of Inhyron?' you ask.[paragraph break]The Baron smiles ruefully. 'What do I think of him? I think he's an arrogant, self-righteous bigot who's obsessed with his family lineage to an unhealthy degree. And my family owes his family everything. So I keep my mouth shut.'"
The repeat text is "[rp] 'it's not a good idea for me to speak ill of the Duke.'"

AM16 is a quip. The menu text is "'What do you think of the Earl of Bresa?'". The display text is "'What do you think of the Earl of Bresa?' you ask.[paragraph break]The Baron looks over to where the Earl is telling crude jokes and stuffing his face at the refreshment table. 'Oh, Bresa's a good fellow,' he says with a smile. 'He doesn't care for the social niceties, and that infuriates some peope. But he's smarter than most give him credit for.'"
The repeat text is "[rp] 'the Earl has his eccentricities, but he's as good a man as anyone here."

AM17 is a quip. The display text is "'Hello again, milady,' says the Baron with a slight bow. 'You are finding the festivities enjoyable, I  hope?'"

